  "description": "THINGS-MEG is a large-scale magnetoencephalographic dataset comprising dense neural recordings from participants viewing thousands of naturalistic object images from the THINGS database. The dataset includes MEG recordings from 4 participants viewing 22,448 unique images (a representative subset of the full THINGS database of 26,107 images) representing 1,854 object concepts across 12 sessions, complemented by structural MRI for source localization and eye-tracking data. This resource enables investigation of the temporal dynamics of visual and semantic object representations in the human brain.",
  "methods_description": "Participants viewed THINGS images presented in rapid succession (1.5±0.2s) during MEG recording while maintaining central fixation. An oddball detection task with artificially-generated images was used to maintain engagement. A subset of 200 images was repeated in each session. T1-weighted MRI scans were acquired for cortical source localization, and eye movements were monitored throughout the experiment via MEG-based eye movement tracking.",
